   <BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
   <FONT COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif">
   <H3>Intended Enhancements and Programme of Data Collation</H3><FONT SIZE=-1>
   <P>The Gazetteer will develop over the coming years into a large knowledge bank
   for thousands of places in Scotland.  It will focus on the history, geography,
   economy and tourist attractions of small and large settlements, as well as on
   the large variety of our countrys geographical features, from rivers and lochs
   to mountains and parks.  It will also bring out the connections between these
   places and Scotlands families and famous people, providing a major reference
   for the public.</P>
   <P>Between 1999 and 2002 we will be adding detailed
   information on these settlements, features, people and families.
   By late-1999 we intend to have entries for all significant settlements and 
   by late-2001
   we aim to have covered the whole of Scotland in some depth.  We will then
   proceed to add smaller settlements and features and fill out these entries.
   <P>Beyond 2002 we hope to continue to enhance the
   Gazetteer by: </P>
   <UL><LI>Adding many more photographs, maps, video clips and sounds from around
   all over Scotland</LI>
   <LI>Historical maps for each town and region from the collection of the
   Royal Scottish Geographical Society</LI>
   <LI>Historical excerpts from Groomes 19th century Ordnance Gazetteer of
   Scotland</LI>
   <LI>Present-day and historical statistics</LI>
   <LI>Information regarding Scotlands local and regional commerce and
   industry  </LI>
   <LI>We are also examining the feasibility of producing fully interactive
   mapping using Geographical Information Systems technology, a
   particular expertise of the Department of Geography at the University of
   Edinburgh.</LI></UL>
   <P>Many more enhancements will be included over the coming years.  We very much welcome your suggestions.</P>
   </FONT></FONT>
